248
00:10:03,601 --> 00:10:06,071
on Hanford, and after a tunnel collapse this May,

249
00:10:06,437 --> 00:10:08,573
they found some of the infrastructure there is

250
00:10:08,673 --> 00:10:11,409
almost comically badly put together.

251
00:10:12,043 --> 00:10:14,112
ANCHOR:<i> Mistakes during  construction are factors</i>

252
00:10:14,212 --> 00:10:16,081
<i> in the dangerous state  of the tunnels.</i>

253
00:10:16,315 --> 00:10:19,084
<i> They're 55 and 60 years old,</i>

254
00:10:19,384 --> 00:10:21,653
<i> well beyond their expected  life span.</i>

255
00:10:21,919 --> 00:10:25,756
<i>In addition, wood beams holding  up the tunnels are eroding,</i>

256
00:10:25,857 --> 00:10:29,594
<i>and what corrodes timber beams?  Radiation.</i>

257
00:10:30,261 --> 00:10:31,162
Yeah!

258
00:10:31,397 --> 00:10:33,932
You can't build something out of wood and expect it

259
00:10:34,033 --> 00:10:36,100
to last forever. You're supposed to have learned that

260
00:10:36,201 --> 00:10:38,570
from the second dumbest of the Three Little Pigs.

261
00:10:38,769 --> 00:10:40,404
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

262
00:10:40,706 --> 00:10:43,308
Hanford... Hanford is a gigantic problem.

263
00:10:43,708 --> 00:10:46,845
And even though it hasn't produced anything for 30 years,

264
00:10:46,946 --> 00:10:48,379
the Department of Energy still spends

265
00:10:48,480 --> 00:10:50,248
nearly two and a half billion dollars a year

266
00:10:50,347 --> 00:10:53,084
on cleaning it up, which is close to ten percent

267
00:10:53,184 --> 00:10:54,485
of its annual budget.

268
00:10:54,852 --> 00:10:56,153
And it is pretty weird

269
00:10:56,455 --> 00:10:58,456
to find out that a place you just heard about

270
00:10:58,690 --> 00:11:00,893
is getting that much of the DOE's money.

271
00:11:01,125 --> 00:11:03,727
It's like finding out that half the Department of Agriculture

272
00:11:03,827 --> 00:11:06,264
budget goes to this moose named Gordon.

273
00:11:06,498 --> 00:11:09,068
I mean, I don't know the right amount,

274
00:11:09,668 --> 00:11:11,870
-but that seems like a lot. -(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

275
00:11:11,970 --> 00:11:14,038
And in case you're thinking, "Well I'm definitely glad that

276
00:11:14,139 --> 00:11:15,507
I don't live near Hanford,"

277
00:11:15,606 --> 00:11:18,242
remember there are nuclear power plants storing waste

278
00:11:18,610 --> 00:11:20,778
all over the country, lots of it in so-called

279
00:11:21,080 --> 00:11:22,480
"spent fuel pools."

280
00:11:22,581 --> 00:11:25,017
That's where nuclear fuel rods are supposed to be

281
00:11:25,116 --> 00:11:26,784
temporarily placed to cool down,

282
00:11:26,884 --> 00:11:28,886
and then put into dry containers,

283
00:11:29,120 --> 00:11:30,054
and then moved

284
00:11:30,154 --> 00:11:31,990
to permanent underground storage sites.

285
00:11:32,090 --> 00:11:34,359
But remember, we don't have one of those.

286
00:11:34,625 --> 00:11:37,394
And in many places those pools are just accumulating

287
00:11:37,495 --> 00:11:38,663
more and more rods.

288
00:11:38,764 --> 00:11:40,399
And while experts say it's highly unlikely,

289
00:11:40,499 --> 00:11:43,836
if a Fukushima-like accident happens at one of those,

290
00:11:43,936 --> 00:11:45,771
the results could be catastrophic.

291
00:11:46,438 --> 00:11:48,506
ANCHOR:<i>  The northeast has a number  of nuclear power plants,</i>

292
00:11:48,606 --> 00:11:51,876
<i>including the Indian Point plant  just outside of New York City.</i>

293
00:11:51,976 --> 00:11:53,745
<i> If any one of those  were to have</i>

294
00:11:53,845 --> 00:11:56,115
<i> a severe  spent fuel pool accident,</i>

295
00:11:58,015 --> 00:12:00,051
<i> you're taking away  a lot of big cities,</i>

296
00:12:00,152 --> 00:12:03,221
<i> a lot of farm lands,  a lot of the United States,</i>

297
00:12:03,654 --> 00:12:05,723
<i>for decades, perhaps centuries.</i>

298
00:12:06,258 --> 00:12:08,494
That's right, lots of big cities.

299
00:12:08,594 --> 00:12:10,829
New York, Hartford, Boston.

300
00:12:11,028 --> 00:12:12,330
And that last one is a real shame,

301
00:12:12,431 --> 00:12:14,799
'cause as I understand it, they only just got

302
00:12:14,899 --> 00:12:16,168
un-racist yesterday.

303
00:12:16,368 --> 00:12:17,569
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS) -So...

304
00:12:17,668 --> 00:12:20,639
I mean, at least they could get to enjoy their new life.

305
00:12:20,839 --> 00:12:22,041
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS) -So...

306
00:12:22,240 --> 00:12:25,143
So, look, it is pretty clear we need to find

307
00:12:25,243 --> 00:12:27,946
a permanent facility to store our most dangerous waste.

308
00:12:28,046 --> 00:12:30,916
And 30 years ago, we actually settled on a site,

309
00:12:31,015 --> 00:12:32,817
Yucca Mountain in Nevada.

310
00:12:33,051 --> 00:12:34,653
Congress passed a law designating it

311
00:12:34,753 --> 00:12:37,122
as our sole candidate for waste storage.

312
00:12:37,221 --> 00:12:39,691
Now since then, we've spent 15 billion dollars

313
00:12:39,791 --> 00:12:40,759
prepping the site,

314
00:12:40,860 --> 00:12:43,062
as you can see from this rather upbeat video.

315
00:12:51,102 --> 00:12:52,903
NARRATOR:<i> Located  about 100 miles</i>

316
00:12:53,004 --> 00:12:54,373
<i> northwest of Las Vegas,</i>

317
00:12:54,673 --> 00:12:57,208
<i> Yucca mountain is the most  thoroughly researched site</i>

318
00:12:57,308 --> 00:12:58,677
<i> of its kind in the world.</i>

319
00:12:58,777 --> 00:13:01,113
<i> Experts throughout the world  agree that the most</i>

320
00:13:01,212 --> 00:13:02,880
<i> feasible and safe method</i>

321
00:13:02,980 --> 00:13:05,617
<i> for disposing of highly radioactive materials</i>

322
00:13:06,451 --> 00:13:08,519
<i> is to store them  deep underground.</i>

323
00:13:09,053 --> 00:13:10,555
That's right. The best place

324
00:13:10,655 --> 00:13:13,257
to put nuclear waste is in a hole deep underground.

325
00:13:13,357 --> 00:13:14,758
Much like Felicity.

326
00:13:15,293 --> 00:13:18,296
Wait. Wait, if she's not there, where is she?

327
00:13:18,397 --> 00:13:20,932
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS) -Ah, Jesus fucking Christ!

328
00:13:21,332 --> 00:13:22,132
Fuck me!

329
00:13:22,232 --> 00:13:24,235
Jesus! Fucking-- Get the fuck away!

330
00:13:25,035 --> 00:13:27,038
(PANTING)

331
00:13:27,438 --> 00:13:29,073
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

332
00:13:29,841 --> 00:13:32,177
(PANTING)

333
00:13:32,510 --> 00:13:33,745
-(AUDIENCE CHEERS) -It's alright. It's okay.

334
00:13:33,845 --> 00:13:34,779
I'm fine.

335
00:13:35,581 --> 00:13:36,447
It's fine.

336
00:13:38,583 --> 00:13:39,583
The point is...

337
00:13:40,619 --> 00:13:43,754
So, Yucca mountain is our permanent storage site.

338
00:13:43,855 --> 00:13:46,225
So the problem is solved, right? Well, no!

339
00:13:46,424 --> 00:13:48,326
Because while the site has been deemed safe,

340
00:13:48,427 --> 00:13:49,961
and the people in the immediate area,

341
00:13:50,061 --> 00:13:52,397
Nye County, actually support the project,

342
00:13:52,496 --> 00:13:54,131
many Nevadans elsewhere in the state

343
00:13:54,331 --> 00:13:55,866
really don't want it.

344
00:13:55,966 --> 00:13:58,336
And their former senator, Harry Reed, lobbied hard,

345
00:13:58,437 --> 00:14:00,672
eventually managing to get Yucca shot down.

346
00:14:00,772 --> 00:14:03,275
Now, to be fair, he did have an alternative plan

347
00:14:03,375 --> 00:14:05,311
for all the states sitting on their nuclear waste,

348
00:14:05,410 --> 00:14:06,611
but to put it mildly,

349
00:14:06,812 --> 00:14:08,746
it was not exactly scientifically-sound.

350
00:14:09,414 --> 00:14:10,915
Leave it on site, where it is.

351
00:14:11,015 --> 00:14:13,784
Leave it where it is, and dry cast storage containers.

352
00:14:14,052 --> 00:14:16,455
If you were smart, what you would do is, uh...

353
00:14:16,688 --> 00:14:17,856
leave this...

354
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:19,658
leave it where it is.

355
00:14:19,758 --> 00:14:20,792
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

356
00:14:20,892 --> 00:14:23,028
"If you're smart, what you would do is leave

357
00:14:23,128 --> 00:14:25,830
the thing where it is" is terrible advice

358
00:14:25,931 --> 00:14:26,998
for dealing with nuclear waste.

359
00:14:27,097 --> 00:14:28,532
Although, it is coincidentally

360
00:14:28,633 --> 00:14:30,936
the title of Britain's bestselling book on parenting.

361
00:14:31,370 --> 00:14:32,870
-But... But... -(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

362
00:14:33,138 --> 00:14:34,639
Here... Here is the truth.

363
00:14:35,005 --> 00:14:37,274
the scientific consensus for decades

364
00:14:37,375 --> 00:14:41,278
has been that leaving it where it is is a really bad idea.

365
00:14:41,379 --> 00:14:44,015
The shutted power plant at San Onofre, in California,

366
00:14:44,115 --> 00:14:46,651
is storing nuclear waste, and it's on a fault line

367
00:14:46,851 --> 00:14:48,519
right next to the ocean.

368
00:14:48,886 --> 00:14:50,388
And that sounds like something you learn

369
00:14:50,489 --> 00:14:52,357
in the first scene of a movie starring The Rock

370
00:14:52,456 --> 00:14:54,024
that you watch on a plane.

371
00:14:54,125 --> 00:14:55,159
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS) -And look,

372
00:14:55,259 --> 00:14:57,261
maybe Yucca is the best place

373
00:14:57,361 --> 00:14:59,630
to store our growing supply of radioactive garbage.

374
00:14:59,831 --> 00:15:00,733
Maybe it's not.

375
00:15:01,166 --> 00:15:04,069
I am not a nuclear scientist. I just have the face of one.

376
00:15:04,369 --> 00:15:06,071
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS) -And... And our--

377
00:15:06,437 --> 00:15:09,006
Our new energy secretary, Rick Perry...

378
00:15:09,206 --> 00:15:10,508
yes, Rick Perry...

379
00:15:10,841 --> 00:15:12,877
has said that he is optimistic about fixing

380
00:15:12,977 --> 00:15:14,411
the whole problem, which does sound great.

381
00:15:14,511 --> 00:15:16,614
Although, he didn't exactly do a great job

382
00:15:16,715 --> 00:15:18,216
at dealing with this disaster.

383
00:15:18,682 --> 00:15:20,052
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

384
00:15:20,251 --> 00:15:22,553
(STUDIO AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

385
00:15:23,187 --> 00:15:25,323
Yeah, that was him on<i> Dancing with the Stars,</i>

386
00:15:25,423 --> 00:15:27,992
and on the basis of that, managing volatile energy

387
00:15:28,092 --> 00:15:29,827
is not really his forte.

388
00:15:30,629 --> 00:15:32,197
But here's the thing. We've been saying

389
00:15:32,298 --> 00:15:34,533
that we are going to fix this for decades now,

390
00:15:34,633 --> 00:15:36,768
and we seem to be no closer to a solution.

391
00:15:36,868 --> 00:15:37,770
And let me show you something

392
00:15:37,870 --> 00:15:39,370
that really drove that fact home to us,

393
00:15:39,471 --> 00:15:40,905
because we've been researching this story

394
00:15:41,005 --> 00:15:43,608
for a couple of weeks now, and just yesterday afternoon,

395
00:15:43,975 --> 00:15:47,345
we stumbled on a TV special from 1977,

396
00:15:47,445 --> 00:15:48,580
the year that I was born.

397
00:15:49,548 --> 00:15:52,418
♪ (MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

398
00:15:55,352 --> 00:15:56,921
NARRATOR:<i>  NBC News presents...</i>

399
00:16:00,357 --> 00:16:02,427
Danger! Radioactive Waste.

400
00:16:03,327 --> 00:16:05,396
Yeah, this problem is so old

401
00:16:05,496 --> 00:16:07,365
they reported on it back when the news was kept

402
00:16:07,466 --> 00:16:09,466
in an America-shaped vault that you had to open

403
00:16:09,567 --> 00:16:10,601
with a crank.

404
00:16:11,035 --> 00:16:13,304
As we watched that yesterday, we gradually

405
00:16:13,404 --> 00:16:15,908
and chillingly realized that by pure coincidence

406
00:16:16,174 --> 00:16:19,343
it hits every beat of the story that we just told you.

407
00:16:19,577 --> 00:16:21,746
It opens with footage of sailors throwing barrels

408
00:16:21,846 --> 00:16:22,780
into the ocean.

409
00:16:22,880 --> 00:16:24,882
It looks at the facilities at Hanford.

410
00:16:25,116 --> 00:16:27,451
It talks about radiation's impact on workers

411
00:16:27,684 --> 00:16:29,353
and on families who live nearby.

412
00:16:29,553 --> 00:16:31,523
And while it doesn't have a radioactive alligator,

413
00:16:31,724 --> 00:16:33,658
it does have radioactive cows.

414
00:16:33,924 --> 00:16:35,760
Which is-- which is still good. Although,

415
00:16:35,860 --> 00:16:38,028
I did prefer our alligator.

416
00:16:38,230 --> 00:16:40,298
I liked it when he went... (HISSES)

417
00:16:40,399 --> 00:16:41,500
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS) -But--

418
00:16:41,832 --> 00:16:43,267
But the most chilling moment

419
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:46,004
in that documentary might be the one where they sit down

420
00:16:46,105 --> 00:16:48,239
with someone in authority, and demand to know

421
00:16:48,339 --> 00:16:50,075
exactly when this will be fixed.

422
00:16:50,375 --> 00:16:52,945
NARRATOR:<i> When you ask when the problem will be solved,</i>

423
00:16:53,044 --> 00:16:54,312
<i> you get answers like this.</i>

424
00:16:54,946 --> 00:16:56,648
WOMAN: What's the realistic time table?

425
00:16:57,514 --> 00:16:59,518
Realistic time table is scheduled to have

426
00:16:59,618 --> 00:17:02,721
a repository in operation by 1985,

427
00:17:03,187 --> 00:17:06,791
with the selection of the sites by the end of 1978

428
00:17:06,892 --> 00:17:07,960
for detailed work.

429
00:17:08,460 --> 00:17:09,326
Exactly.

430
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:12,163
Nuclear waste is a problem we were supposed to have dealt

431
00:17:12,262 --> 00:17:14,832
with in the 1980's and still cannot solve,

432
00:17:14,932 --> 00:17:18,670
much like this Rubik's Cube that I always carry with me.

433
00:17:19,070 --> 00:17:22,540
You are my Jean Valjean, cube, and, one day,

434
00:17:22,974 --> 00:17:25,242
-I shall defeat you. -(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

435
00:17:25,442 --> 00:17:27,679
And at the end of that special, remember,

436
00:17:27,778 --> 00:17:31,249
40 years ago, the correspondent delivers this special message.

437
00:17:31,782 --> 00:17:33,851
The waste increases every minute.

438
00:17:34,553 --> 00:17:37,088
The solution of where to put it is years away.

439
00:17:37,556 --> 00:17:39,525
<i> And none of the previous  solutions has worked.</i>

440
00:17:40,893 --> 00:17:42,826
<i> We are accustomed  in this country to act</i>

441
00:17:42,926 --> 00:17:44,762
<i> only in times of crisis.</i>

442
00:17:45,730 --> 00:17:47,266
<i> But with nuclear waste,</i>

443
00:17:47,499 --> 00:17:49,701
<i> when the crisis comes,  it will be too late.</i>

444
00:17:50,402 --> 00:17:52,971
And that was from four decades ago.

445
00:17:53,070 --> 00:17:56,240
We have already waited way too long to resolve this issue.

446
00:17:56,340 --> 00:17:58,308
And we are dancing with trouble here.

447
00:17:58,509 --> 00:18:00,345
So if any one says the government

448
00:18:00,444 --> 00:18:02,146
can just continue to wait,

449
00:18:02,247 --> 00:18:04,916
they are much like a house with no toilet.

450
00:18:05,250 --> 00:18:07,184
Absolutely full of shit.

451
00:18:07,285 --> 00:18:08,887
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS, APPLAUDS)

